[{"id":"VR834504","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows four point charges each with a charge of positive q placed at the corners of a square with side lengths of L.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834504.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Four positively charged particles, each with the same charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive q\"><math alttext=\"positive q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>, are initially located at the corners of a square of side length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\"><math alttext=\"L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>L</mi></math></span></span>, as shown in the figure. In this configuration, the electric potential energy of the four-particle system is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>. External forces then move the particles closer together to a final configuration where the particles form a square of side length <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L over 2\"><math alttext=\"L over 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></span></span>. If <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is the total work done by the external forces in moving the particles from the initial to the final configuration, how does <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> compare to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>? What evidence or reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR834504_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The total charge of the system does not change.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The electric potential energy of the system is doubled.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>. <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is equal to the change in potential energy of the system.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"W\"><math alttext=\"W\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>W</mi></math></span></span> is greater than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub L\"><math alttext=\"U sub L\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The particles repel, so positive work is done by the external forces.</p>"],"answer":1}]